            <span id="ChapterParagraphOne">
            <span id="BigFirstLetterText">R</span>umor has it that we came from a northern part of China called Xinjiang, and you can tell by the way we look. We don't really look Chinese–the hairiness, the closeness of our eyes, and the features of our bodies. When Auntie Ellis was young, she was really, really pretty. Not that she's not pretty now, but back then, she was a knock-out. She didn’t look like a typical Chinese person. Neither do I. Even now, when I go to Hong Kong, they look at me. If they ask me a question and I think a little bit, they start using English, because they see me as not exactly Chinese. So rumor has it that we emigrated from the north, and it took 500 years of moving slowly from Xinjiang all the way to Liaoning, another province, until we got to southern China and settled in a place called Hung Wei Village in Zhongshan Prefecture. That's where the story stops. You can trace some of our lineage, because we thought we had been there in southern China for 22 generations. But according to my father, we came from the north and slowly migrated. I ran into other relatives who also gave me the same story.<br />
            </span>

