            <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
            My great-grandfather was in imports-exports, or railways. He went down to Australia, married, and we have a branch of the family down there. I have no idea who they are, but we have a branch. He came back and was forced to give up his land. He bought a lot of land with the money that he earned, figuring that the Japanese could bomb all they wanted; a little hole could be filled up with dirt and would be gone. He never thought about the Communists. They locked him up in jail because he was a rich land owner, and back then, you had to give up all of your land. The story from my father was they had him kneel in glass to torture him. He got to the stage where he committed suicide.  
            </span>
            <span id="SEE_MORE"><a href="#" id="restofstory-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory" class="more">
                <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    My grandfather was a village chief and ran gambling casinos and so forth. Back then you had to do what you needed to survive, and the family prospered. Apparently they had a big house and mansions, and he had several wives. One of the wives came out to Hawaii when she was about fifty, but after that one meeting, she was gone. The grandmother’s side never took her seriously, so she disappeared. <br /><br />

                    Grandfather decided to move down to Hong Kong during the World War and the war in China, and my father went down to Hong Kong, too. They felt it was the best time to go. But when you're rich and you own land in China, you smoke opium. The story goes that the village wanted to open Chinese trade, and what they had to do was sell opium, which is heroin–very addictive. Grandfather picked up the opium and couldn't get rid of it. He died around age 65. I was around three or four years old, and he would take me around. I remember it a little bit. <br /><br />

                    My father was the number one son. That means that you have a lot of responsibilities thrown on you. A lot of responsibility. It was more than just working and bringing food for your family; he had to take care of Uncle John (Yi Sok), Uncle Summie (Sam Sok), Gujie (the youngest), and the rest of the family. He told me once that they had twelve brothers and sisters, but a lot of them died in the war so they ended up with only four. He, being the father figure, had to take care of them. He brought them meals, gave them spending money, lined them up for work; whatever he had to do. <br /><br />

                    The story goes that my father was working as an artist at this theater called Roxy Theater, Lok Sing Hei Yun. By the way, that's where my name came from, and where Uncle Gansin's name came from: Ga Lok Ga Sing–Roxy Theater. The theater burned down. It’s relevant because what my father did back then was paint huge posters. You can see some of the work he's done with old movies, like Gone with the Wind. He would paint Clark Gable, stick it up, and people would come see the movies. Uncle John, Iso, came down from the village and was apprenticed to my father, learning how to paint. My father said he was so good he could do a big poster in one day. The difficulty was with the heads, because people can recognize if you're off. He was really good at fixing the proportions. One day Uncle John fell asleep while smoking, and that <a id="underline" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l1GXJBIkb74"> burned the whole theater down</a>. They were out of a job–unemployed. It was lucky that nobody died. <br /><br />

                    Next he started painting, because back then, it all depended on what skills you had. At the time he had had one teacher who taught him in three months. At the end of the third month the teacher said, "Sum Li, you know everything there is to know. I can't teach you anymore." <br /><br />

                    He wanted to be an architect and then one day he had an opportunity. A friend came to him and said, "Why don't you bid for this project? I think you're really good." <br /><br />

                    My father said, “I’m only an artist." <br /><br />

                    "You're more than an artist. You're a designer, an interior designer. You can build things." <br /><br />

                    "Okay, I'll put in a bid." <br /><br />

                    The bid was for the interior design of a chain of restaurants. And he won! He created a business called the Li Sum Art Studio. It was his first business of his own. He rented out a garage, which, by the way, is right across the street from where we're living in Hong Kong now. You can see that same garage, but now they use it to fix cars. He worked very hard, got project after project, and his name was quite well known. Now when I go back to Hong Kong and ask friends in the industry about "Fitting Out Interior Design," they've heard of it. "Oh, that's what happened to Li Sum!” There are a lot of newspaper clippings they still have today. Uncle Gansin has those clippings of things father did in Hong Kong at that time. He was very proud of his history. 
                </span>

