            <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
            
                Hong Kong was in chaos. There were times of riots. Unemployment was at an all-time 
                high. So many times in their lives they did not have jobs, and despite this adversity that 
                they faced, they were able to suppress it and ride over it. They didn't sell us; they didn't 
                throw us out into the street; they didn't starve us. Despite that they had only a few 
                dollars in their pockets, they put us through school. They struggled to make connections 
                so we could have schools to go to. 

 
            </span>
            <span id="SEE_MORE"><a href="#" id="restofstory2-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory2');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory2" class="more">
                <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    It's amazing how my dad provided for the family despite all this adversity. For example, I 
                    remember we were living in the garage in Hong Kong, and there was a car that 
                    somehow hit one of our family members. Then the woman came into our house and 
                    apologized profusely for how sorry she was that she hit one of us. My dad immediately 
                    took the opportunity and said, "What kind of profession are you?" She said, "I'm the 
                    principal of an elementary school." In Hong Kong it's not like in America, where 
                    everybody goes to school. In Hong Kong you have to have money and connections. Not 
                    only money; you have to have connections in order to even go to school. So my dad 
                    said, "Oh, you know, don't worry. I have a daughter here. We're hoping that she can go 
                    to school. She's six years old." Which was me! That's how he got me into Precious 
                    Blood Elementary School. It’s in my memory. I still remember that woman sitting in the 
                    chair, and we're huddling around because this stranger has come into our house. 
                    <br /><br />

                    That's one thing about my dad: he was very generous to strangers. I still remember he 
                    would invite strangers to our house to sleep for a few days, and then let them go. One 
                    time it was refugees from Russia. They said, "We're running away because of political 
                    issues and for political asylum." My dad would be so generous to let them sleep in our 
                    house. I mean, we didn’t have a house, but we had that garage! Everybody slept there. 
                    There was no division of rooms. Everybody slept in a big room and everyone had 
                    different beds. My dad was so nice to let them sleep there. That's the person my dad 
                    was—very generous. 
                    <br /><br />

                    He also took the opportunity to support us. So, that principal—to make a long story short—she gave us a discount, gave us a scholarship, and allowed me to go to school in the 
                    school down the street. That was really nice, and it's amazing how my dad survived in 
                    this world of little resources with little skill, little language skill. I guess that's what 
                    brought him the strength to come to America, even with little ability to achieve, and he 
                    was able to raise us.
                </span>

