            <div id="restofstory5" class="more">
                <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    Despite the limited years of education my father had because of the war, his Chinese was really good. At one stage, because of a problem with his eyes, he learned to be a Chinese doctor. He bought different books, read them, underlined them, and practiced on us. He would make his own secret formula and drink it. He was able to learn things from nothing. His Chinese was so good that we had no clue what many words he used were because he was reading at a university level. And he could write. His writing was very cursive–difficult to read–and the character and language he used was at quite a high level. I know that because when I showed some of his letters to educated people, they said, "Wow. This is a person who writes with a lot of poetry." 
                    <br /><br />

                    If you look at how my parents tried to educate us, there are some lessons that come through. Education is key if you want to get out of the neighborhood and make something of yourself. They tried to brainwash us, even when we were young. "If you don't get a college education, don't come back." Dad would teach us about ethics, in his own way. One day he taught Gansin and me about the birds and the bees. I was eleven and he was eight. It was funny because we were in the car and didn't know what was going on. All of a sudden my father was in our faces. I looked at Gansin and Gansin looked at me. "What is this? Is this for real?" Then we started to think, "Hmm. Maybe what he's telling is the truth." Dad had heard it from my mom, who told him, "You better talk to those guys about the birds and the bees, otherwise they're going to get into trouble." So we learned it like that, in five seconds! That's growing up.
                    <br /><br />

                    He encouraged us to be good at what we did. There was a competition at a local department store, and we were supposed to use watercolor to paint something. And guess what? I won! I won in my age group, and as a result they gave me a world clock. I had to win because my father was an artist, and he guided you on what colors to bring out. I didn't know I could draw.
