            <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
            
               I was learning at that time how to use chopsticks. I was four or five, and kids usually have plastic bowls, so I was grabbing something, and I couldn't grab it. Next thing I know, my father slapped the rice bowl, and it flew and hit the wall. I was looking at that, thinking, "That's interesting." He was mad because I couldn't properly eat a meal; I couldn't pick up a little bean. He said, "Until you pick up a bean, you're not eating again." I was in shock. "Ohhhh!" Of course, my mom and father always played this game. Over the next day my mom set out a bowl of beans, real beans, and I would pick at them, using chopsticks: one, two, three, four, until I could do it. It only took a day, and I could eat again. It was good cop, bad cop. Father was always the mean one, and mom was the caring one. But you know, it worked. That's how I learned to use chopsticks.
 
